ham, Kent, Anglie","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Anglie"},"da":{"1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Afdød","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1375":"1375","about 1389":"omkring 1389","about 1410":"omkring 1410","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"nl":{"1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Overleden","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1375":"1375","about 1389":"circa 1389","about 1410":"circa 1410","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"en":{"1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1375":"1375","about 1389":"about 1389","about 1410":"about 1410","1417":"1417","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name, from Middle English <i>bakere</i>, Old English <i>bæcere</i>, a derivative of <i>bacan</i> ‘to bake’. It may have been used for someone whose special task in the kitchen of a great house or castle was the baking of bread, but since most humbler households did their own baking in the Middle Ages, it may also have referred to the owner of a communal oven used by the whole village. The right to be in charge of this and exact money or loaves in return for its use was in many parts of the country a hereditary feudal privilege. Compare   Miller  . Less often the surname may have been acquired by someone noted for baking particularly fine bread or by a baker of pottery or bricks.","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘baker’, for example Dutch   Bakker  , German   Becker   and   Beck  , French   Boulanger   and <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ), Czech <b>Pekař</b>, Slovak <b>Pekár</b>, and Croatian   Pekar  .","History: Baker was established as an early immigrant surname in Puritan New England. Among others, two men called Remember Baker (father and son) lived at Woodbury, CT, in the early 17th century, and an Alexander Baker arrived in Boston, MA, in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Miller","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a miller. The standard modern vocabulary word represents the northern Middle English term <i>miller</i>, an agent derivative of <i>mille</i> ‘mill’, reinforced by Old Norse <i>mylnari</i> (see   Milner  ). In southern, western, and central England   Millward   (literally, ‘mill keeper’) was the usual term. In North America, the surname <i>Miller</i> has absorbed many cognate surnames from other languages, for example German <b>Müller</b> (see   Mueller  ), Dutch   Mulder   and   Molenaar  , French   Meunier  , Italian   Molinaro  , Spanish   Molinero  , Hungarian <b>Molnár</b> (see   Molnar  ), Slovenian, Croatian, and Serbian   Mlinar  , Polish <b>Młynarz</b> or <b>Młynarczyk</b> (see   Mlynarczyk  ). <i>Miller</i> (including in the senses below) is the seventh most frequent surname in the US.","South German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Müller</b> ‘miller’ (see   Mueller  ) and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in other European countries, notably in Poland, Denmark, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), and Czechia; compare 3 below.","Americanized form of Polish, Czech, Croatian, Serbian, and Slovenian   Miler   ‘miller’, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Baxter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>baxter</i> ‘baker’ (from Old English <i>bæcestre</i> ‘baker’, earlier ‘female baker’, the feminine equivalent of <i>bæcere</i>). Compare   Baker  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Baker III was born in 1384, in Faversham, Kent, England, his father, John Baker VII, was 29 and his mother, Joane Fryer, was 9. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Thomas. He died in 1420, in his hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1384–1420":"1384–1420","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1375":"1375","about 1389":"umbes 1389","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1417":"1417","Fave